items.title: How to Build Geospatial Analytics with Python and Oracle Database

items.title: How to Build “Kubernetes-Native” Applications
items.abstract: Many companies today are developing applications specifically to run on Kubernetes. These applications don’t just use Kubernetes as a deployment platform. They persist data in Kubernetes’ own etcd database, use Kubernetes custom resource definitions (CRDs) as data access objects, encode business logic in Kubernetes controllers, and build their own API layer on the Kubernetes API server. They use “kubectl” as their own CLI. Kubernetes-native applications are easy to build, can run anywhere, and are massively scalable. Learn more in this session.

items.title: How to Create a Fluent API DSL with Lambda Builders
items.abstract: LesFurets.com’s dOOv framework is trying to solve a common problem with software: performance versus readability versus type safety. Since Java 8, lambdas offer the ability to compose functions at runtime with high performance. LesFurets.com built a fluent API, using lambdas to write validation and mapping logic with a DSL. By visiting the DSL abstract syntax tree at runtime, it enables the written application rules to be introspected and profiled. In this BOF, the speakers discuss how the framework was designed, failure cause analysis, AST rewriting, and the issues they encountered in generating the natural language output.

items.title: How to Create an Architecture for Web Test Automation
items.abstract: Automating tests on a web front end is not the most important level in the test automation pyramid, but it is critical from a user perspective. If it is not done with minimal architecture and good use of software engineering practices, we will have a lot of maintenance and abandonment of tests in this layer. items.title: How to Deal with Java Troubles on Microservices
items.abstract: On microservices, manual troubleshooting may be difficult, so automating log analysis and anomaly detection become important. How about the next step ? On traditional systems, engineers have identified the causes of problems, but how about on microservices? Machine learning comes to mind, but most of that needs sufficient trouble cases, which may not be available in a limited test period. A Bayesian network may meet our needs, because it can utilize human knowledge. Such networks have been employed in medical diagnosis, for example. This session discusses how to use a Bayesian network for Java troubleshooting manually and aims to show a proof of concept for automating Java troubleshooting.

items.title: How to Make MySQL Work with Raft
items.abstract: For its cloud environment, Alibaba hoped MySQL Cluster could do the failover and choose the new master node by the instance automatically, without third-party middleware. So it built the Raft protocol into MySQL. In the MySQL/Raft version, every cluster usually has three nodes—one master and two slaves—but it can support more nodes. When the master node is down, the cluster can choose the new master via the Raft protocol and use Flashback to roll back the committed transactions if needed, to make sure all the nodes are the same. Learn more in this session.

items.title: How to Take Advantage of Optimizer Improvements in MySQL 8.0
items.abstract: MySQL 8.0 introduces several improvements to the query optimizer that may give improved performance for your queries. This presentation looks at what kind of queries the different improvements apply to, and the focus is on what you can do to get the most out of the optimizer improvements. The main topics are changes to the optimizer cost model, histograms, and new optimizer hints, but other improvements to how MySQL executes queries are also covered. The presentation includes many practical examples of how you can get a significant speedup for your MySQL queries.

items.title: How to Use JSON in MySQL Wrong
items.abstract:
The JSON data type and functions that support it constitute one of the most interesting features introduced in MySQL 5.7 for application developers. But no feature is a “golden hammer.” We need to apply a little expertise to get the best result and avoid misusing it. This session shows practical examples that work well with JSON and other scenarios in which conventional columns perform better. Questions addressed in this presentation:
• How much space does JSON data use, compared to conventional data?
• What is the performance of querying JSON versus conventional data?
• How do I create indexes for JSON data?
• What kind of data is best to store in JSON?
• How do I get the best of both worlds?

items.title: How to Use the new JDBC 4.3 Sharding API for Massive OLTP Scaling
items.abstract: The key to linear scaling for OLTP workloads is data-dependent routing. JDK9 introduced the sharding API for JDBC 4.3 to enable data-dependent routing. In this session, see how to use this new JDBC API for massive OLTP scaling with the YCSB and SwingBench benchmarks and how to configure and code both the Oracle Sharding feature of Oracle Database and the Oracle TimesTen Scaleout feature of Oracle TimesTen In-Memory Database to use data-dependent routing for massive scalability. Examples include sharding keys, ConnectionBuilders, and data sources.

items.title: HTML5 Web Components State of the Union
items.abstract:
Several years ago, Web Components was announced as a powerful approach to building applications by using reusable widgets. The key difference between Web Components and other approaches is that it’s actually part of HTML5, so it’s built in to the browser itself. The promise is that we will have reusable components that can be used with different JavaScript frameworks or without any framework at all. So, have they lived up to the hype? What is the status of the Web Components specs? Which browsers implement them? Do they really work with different JavaScript frameworks? Come to this session to get answers to these and other questions. Takeaways:
• What Web Components are
• Current and future level of browser support
• How they work with existing frameworks

items.title: Implement Your Own Type System in 45 Minutes
items.abstract: Many developers view type theory as abstruse and confusing. It’s not! This session shows you the four simple components of a type system: the types, their subtyping relationships, how to give a type to each expression in your program, and what operations are illegal. To design a type system, just specify these four things. Starting from nothing, in 45 minutes, the presenters will create a type checker that detects real errors in real programs. Their type checker will handle all Java constructs, such as generics, subtyping, and lambdas. Their type system will detect errors in the use of the Optional type that would otherwise go undetected until runtime. You will also be ready to use dozens of freely available pluggable type systems to improve code quality.

items.title: Improving Editing in IDEs with Structured Program Editing via JavaFX
items.abstract: The original attempts at structured editing, in the 1980s, did not catch on. Despite attempts to free programming from a plain grid of characters and move to editing syntax trees, implementations were still in text-mode interfaces, using...a grid of characters. Modern GUI toolkits offer a lot more options when it comes to presenting and manipulating structured programs—JavaFX, for example, has strong support for complex GUIs, animated transitions, and more. This session demonstrates frame-based editing in Stride, a structured editor that supports all the power of Java and has now been added to the BlueJ educational IDE. The presentation shows how structured editing can easily be used to develop applications and how it may influence how we all edit our code in the future.

items.title: Instant Startup and Low Footprint for Java
items.abstract: GraalVM is an integrated, polyglot, high-performance execution environment for dynamic, static, and native languages. One of the abilities of GraalVM is to compile Java programs ahead of time into native images that offer performance comparable to running on the JVM but have instant startup times and much lower runtime overhead. You’ll also see how to configure native image generation, work around the limitations, and patch your application to use native images.

items.title: Istio and Envoy: Enabling Sidecars for Microservices
items.abstract: The migration from monolith to microservices has empowered engineering teams to develop modular code quickly and efficiently. Although it offers many benefits, this movement has also introduced challenges—namely how to enable fast, secure communication across microservices. One solution to container networking for polyglot microservices is the sidecar model, in which a separate process that manages all network traffic is deployed alongside your microservice. This session explores the benefits of sidecars and shows how they are implemented through two open source projects: Envoy and Istio. By examining how these technologies could be used in both Kubernetes and Cloud Foundry, users will be introduced to the true potential of sidecars.

participants.bio:
Frank Munz works as a Senior Technical Evangelist for Amazon Web Services. He is an expert in middleware and distributed computing. He earned a Ph.D. in computer science from the Technische Universität München with summa cum laude for his work on distributed computing and brain research. He published more than 20 peer reviewed scientific papers in computer science and medicine. When he was 16 he developed and sold his first computer program (a mini e-business suite). In what seems a previous life now, Frank was part of the research group that won the nobel price in medicine for linking the HPV virus to cancer - work that lead to to the development of a vacine later. 

In 2011 Frank received the Oracle Technologist of the Year award for cloud computing. Frank was honoured as Oracle ACE Director by Oracle in 2013 yet continues to work as an independent IT consultant. In 2017 Frank was nominated to be an Oracle Developer Champion. Since 2018 Frank works as a Senior AWS Tech Evangelist.

Frank has over 15 years experience working for and on behalf of top middleware vendors and consultancies such as ConSol, Sun, BEA, TIBCO and Oracle, throughout Europe and Australia as a software architect, project manager and developer. In 2007 Frank founded munz & more - a cutting-edge consultancy focusing on Oracle middleware and cloud computing (see http://www.munzandmore.com).

Frank is the published author of several top selling computer science books. His first book about Middleware and AWS was published a year before Oracle announced its public cloud. He also published one of the best selling Oracle WebLogic Server books ever.

He loves to talk about features and showstoppers and frequently speaks at conferences all over the world.

When Frank is not working, he enjoys travelling in Latin America, skiing in the Alps, tapas in Spain, and scuba diving in Australia.

Follow him now on twitter: @frankmunz

items.abstract: Let’s be honest: the amount of data collected by applications nowadays is growing at a scary pace. Many of them need to handle billions of users generating and consuming data at an incredible speed. Maybe you are wondering how to create an application like this? What is needed? No matter your project size, you can take it to the next level today.

items.title: Jakarta EE: What Is It and What Does It Mean for Enterprise Java?
items.abstract:
Java EE has been the dominant enterprise Java standard for well over a decade. With the release of Jakarta EE, we all have a chance to collaborate and build on the good things it inherits while working to evolve those pieces that were perhaps never quite what was needed. What does this mean for the future of enterprise Java and traditional Java application servers? Attend this session to gain an understanding of where Jakarta EE is heading and how you can help drive the future of enterprise Java. You’ll discover
• The importance of enterprise Java and the promising future of Jakarta EE
• How the move to the Eclipse foundation changes the way enterprise Java evolves and how you can contribute

items.title: Jamming with a Quantum Computer: A Musical Journey into Quantum Computing
items.abstract:
Musical improvisation is the creative activity of composing music "in the moment" while performing it, often in a jam session with other musicians. Although composing and performing music is a creative process, the underlying musical style informs the probabilities of note and rhythmic choices that the musician makes.

In this session, James will give an introduction to quantum computing, cover a bit of music theory, and demonstrate how a quantum computer can compose music and participate in a musical jam session. He will then discuss the development and implementation of the Quantum Music Composer application on an IBM quantum computer.

items.abstract: In a world of containers, we expect safety and security to become increasingly important. We also expect sprawl in the form of many instances, a mix of different applications, heterogeneous machines, and heterogeneous container configurations. And Java’s characteristics make it ideal for container deployment. Oracle is committed to having Java remain the first choice for deployments in the cloud, especially in containerized environments. In this session, hear from Oracle’s Java luminaries committed to keeping Java the first choice for container deployments.

Mikael holds a master's degree in Computer Science from the Royal Institute of Technology (KTH) in Stockholm and is based in Santa Clara, CA.

items.title: Java Debugging Tips
items.abstract: If you really want to find out what goes on inside your Java application, the debugger is your best choice. Are you aware of all the things modern debuggers can do? With Java language advances such as lambdas and streams and rapid improvements by the IDE vendors, it is a good time to revisit Java debugging. This session goes through some common use cases and solves them with debugging features and strategies in IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, and NetBeans: smart breakpoints and stepping, lambdas, monitoring classes and instances, concurrency, and more. So come along for some debugger magic!
